# Day 04 - File Permissions + Ownership

## Theory
- Every file in Linux has permissions — they control who can read, write, and execute it
- Wrong permissions = security risk or broken app
- This is asked in every DevOps interview!

### Reading Permissions (ls -la)
```
-rwxr-xr-- 1 john devs 4096 file.sh
```
| Position | Meaning |
|----------|---------|
| 1 | `-` = regular file, `d` = directory, `l` = link |
| 2-4 | Owner permissions (r=read, w=write, x=execute) |
| 5-7 | Group permissions (`-` means no permission) |
| 8-10 | Others permissions |

### Permission Numbers
| Number | Meaning |
|--------|---------|
| r = 4 | read |
| w = 2 | write |
| x = 1 | execute |
| - = 0 | no permission |

### Common Permission Sets
| Value | Breakdown | Use case |
|-------|-----------|---------|
| `755` | rwx(7) r-x(5) r-x(5) | Owner all, Group read+exec, Others read+exec |
| `644` | rw-(6) r--(4) r--(4) | Owner read+write, Group read, Others read |
| `600` | rw-(6) ---(0) ---(0) | Only owner can read and write (private!) |
| `777` | rwx(7) rwx(7) rwx(7) | Everyone can do everything (NOT for production!) |
| `400` | r--(4) ---(0) ---(0) | Read only even for owner |

## Commands Learned

### chmod — Change Permissions
| Command | What it does |
|---------|-------------|
| `ls -la` | See permissions for all files |
| `chmod 755 file` | Set permissions using numbers |
| `chmod 644 file` | Set read+write for owner, read for others |
| `chmod 600 file` | Private file — only owner can read/write |
| `chmod +x file` | Add execute permission for everyone |
| `chmod -x file` | Remove execute permission |
| `chmod u+w file` | Add write permission for user (owner) |
| `chmod g-w file` | Remove write permission from group |
| `chmod o+r file` | Add read permission for others |
| `chmod -R 755 dir/` | Change permissions for folder + everything inside |

### chown — Change Ownership
| Command | What it does |
|---------|-------------|
| `chown john file` | Change owner of file to john |
| `chown john:devs f` | Change owner to john AND group to devs |
| `chown -R john dir/` | Change owner for folder + everything inside |
| `chgrp devs file` | Change only the group of a file |

### Info Commands
| Command | What it does |
|---------|-------------|
| `stat file` | See full details including permissions in octal |
| `umask` | See default permission mask for new files |
| `whoami` | Note your username |

## Key Takeaways
- `755` = scripts and folders (owner can edit, everyone can run)
- `644` = config files (owner can edit, everyone can read)
- `600` = private files like keys/secrets (only owner can access)
- `777` = never use in production — massive security risk
- `/etc/shadow` is permission denied even for regular users — use `sudo` to read it
- Always `chmod +x` a script before running it

## Script Written Today

**`day04/permissions_demo.sh`**
```bash
#!/bin/bash
# Permissions Demo Script - Day 04

echo "=== Creating test files ==="
touch public.txt private.txt executable.sh

echo "=== Setting permissions ==="
chmod 644 public.txt
chmod 600 private.txt
chmod 755 executable.sh

echo "=== Result ==="
ls -la public.txt private.txt executable.sh

echo "=== Stat of private file ==="
stat private.txt
```

